    "John Trapp": "Whosoever toucheth the carcass. ] This and the like signified that all, even the least sins, are to be purged through Christ, and carefully cast away.\nVer.\n24. Whosoever toucheth the carcass.] This and the like signified that all, even the least sins, are to be purged through Christ, and carefully cast away.\nVer.",
    "Lloyd R. Bailey": "Where does a new paragraph begin? Ambiguity about this arises from the nature\nof the Hebrew Text itself. The language was originally written (from right to left!) as an\nunbroken string of consonants. This means that there was no indication of where a sentence ended,\nno punctuation to divide clauses, no separation of consonants into individual words (there are a few\nexceptions where a \u201cdot\u201d was inserted for this purpose), and no use of vowels.\nIf \u201cX\u201d represents any consonant, a line of early Hebrew would look like this: XXXXXXXXXXXXX . . . ,\nwith no division into words, sentences, or paragraphs. To make matters worse, there was no such\nthing as a \u201ccapital\u201d letter by means of which, in modern writing, the beginning of a new sentence is\nsignaled.\nThis did not create as much confusion as we might think, and this for two reasons:\n(1) The average person could not read and write, leaving only a few well-trained experts to handle\nthe task. Such experts consisted mainly of governmental bureaucrats and priests (i.e., employees of\nthe king and of the temple).\n(2) The written material consisted largely of what we might call \u201cstandard forms\u201d: correspondence,\nfinancial documents (such as loans), sacred liturgical texts, and so on. Thus, one knew roughly what\ntexts was about and should say, and the priests might even have them committed to memory (as\nsome clergy do with contemporary liturgies). Thus the written copy was little more than a \u201cprompt\u201d in\ncase of need.\nAs a simple illustration of this situation, consider the following well known biblical text in English. I\nhave written it without division into individual words, but nonetheless it will be decipherable to the\naverage person who attends Christian worship: \u201courfatherwhoartinheaven.\u201d\nIn most cases such a system of writing prevented no difficulties. The letters could be separated\nmentally into words in only one way if the sentence were to \u201cmake sense\u201d: \u201cOur Father who art in\nheaven.\u201d In a few locations, however, an alternative division would be possible and things still read\nsmoothly. Consider the following silly (non-biblical) illustration: \u201ctheyhaveabandonedward.\u201d Does that\nmean: \u201cThey have abandoned Ward\u201d . . . or, \u201cThey have a band on Edward\u201d?\nFor the work of the Massoretes in adding vowels to the purely consonantal text, see the discussion\n[v_Lev_10_18] of Lev 10:\nv. 24\nThe concluding verse of the chapter adds a new constituency to\nwhich the directives have been addressed: \u201call the people of Israel\u201d\n(contrast"
